ps://api.github.com/repos/datalad/datalad/labels/credentials", "name": "credentials", "color": "768F68", "default": false, "description": "Issues concerning credential(-management)"}], "state": "open", "locked": false, "assignee": null, "assignees": [], "milestone": null, "comments": 1, "created_at": "2021-03-14T13:25:23Z", "updated_at": "2021-07-17T14:06:11Z", "closed_at": null, "author_association": "MEMBER", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "A credential name is presently described as:\r\n\r\n```\r\nname : str\r\n            Name of the credential, as it would be identified by in the centralized\r\n            storage of credentials\r\n ```\r\n\r\nHowever, since https://github.com/datalad/datalad/pull/5491 it is now more obvious that the provided name needs to be chosen carefully. The keyring wrapper will perform a lookup of an environment variable that could provide credentials. FOr that lookup to work, the name must be a valid environment variable name(part). Using hostnames, which are not too far fetched for a name will not work, because they contain a dot (or two), which most shells are not happy with. Given that these implications are all but obvious, DataLad should take care of this, IMHO.", "closed_by": null, "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/datalad/datalad/issues/5495/reactions", "total_count": 0, "+1": 0, "-1": 0, "laugh": 0, "hooray": 0, "confused": 0, "heart": 0, "rocket": 0, "eyes": 0}, "timeline_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/datalad/datalad/issues/5495/timeline", "performed_via_github_app": null}